  "slug": "yorkshire-curd-tart",
  "title": "Yorkshire curd tart",
  "subtitle": "The old Yorkshire cheese and currant tart, scented with nutmeg",
  "excerpt": "A filling of fresh curd cheese, currants, butter, and egg, lightly spiced with nutmeg and baked in a shortcrust case. A regional British tart with roots in the dairy farming of the Yorkshire Dales.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Yorkshire curd tart is documented in Florence White, Good Things in England (1932), Project Gutenberg, as a regional specialty of the Yorkshire Dales connected to the sheep-farming and dairy calendar. The curd filling made from fresh cheese, currants, and nutmeg is attested in Yorkshire cookery from the eighteenth century and remains a specialty of Dales farmers' markets and tearooms.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "About Yorkshire curd tart",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Yorkshire curd tart is one of the old regional British pastries that most people outside Yorkshire have never tried. The filling is made from ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "curd cheese",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpa9xb9l0000t0v4wh79nlgd"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ", the fresh, mild dairy product made by separating milk curds from whey, mixed with butter, currants, egg, and sugar, then generously spiced with nutmeg. The result is a filling that is light, slightly grainy, and fragrant; less sweet than a cheesecake and much less rich.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "True curd cheese from a farm dairy gives the best flavour, but drained cottage cheese or ricotta produces a very similar result at home. The pastry case is not blind baked; the filling is placed in the raw case and everything bakes together, which gives a softer base, this is traditional.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Ingredients",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "ingredientsList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "ingredientItem",
            "attrs": {
              "unit": "g",
              "prepNote": "for the pastry",
              "quantity": 200,
              "isOptional": false,
              "ingredientSlug": "plain-flour"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "ingredientItem",
            "attrs": {
              "unit": "g",
              "prepNote": "cold, for the pastry; plus 50 g softened for the filling",
              "quantity": 100,
              "isOptional": false,
              "ingredientSlug": "unsalted-butter"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "ingredientItem",
            "attrs": {
              "unit": "g",
              "prepNote": "for the pastry",
              "quantity": 20,
              "isOptional": false,
